q {
Q:"The subset \\(A\\) of \\(B\\) which is different from the set \\(B\\) itself, is called a."
A:"a"
O:a) "Proper subset", b) "Improper subset", c) "Subset", d) "Equal set"
R:"By definition in set theory, if every element of \\(A\\) is in \\(B\\) but \\(A \\neq B\\), then \\(A\\) is a proper subset of \\(B\\). An improper subset is the set itself."
}

q {
Q:"The number \\(0.123456789123456789\\ldots\\) is:"
A:"b"
O:a) "An irrational number", b) "A rational number", c) "A whole number", d) "A negative number"
R:"The decimal has a repeating pattern of \\(123456789\\), which means it can be expressed as a fraction of two integers. Therefore, it is a rational number."
}

q {
Q:"Every integer number is also a:"
A:"d"
O:a) "Irrational number", b) "Whole number", c) "Natural number", d) "Rational number"
R:"Any integer \\(n\\) can be written as \\(n/1\\), which satisfies the definition of a rational number (ratio of two integers where the denominator is non-zero)."
}

q {
Q:"The number \\(\\sqrt{n}\\), where \\(n\\) is a prime number, is a:"
A:"b"
O:a) "Rational number", b) "Irrational number", c) "Natural number", d) "Integer number"
R:"The square root of any prime number cannot be expressed as a ratio of integers and has a non-terminating, non-repeating decimal expansion, making it irrational."
}

q {
Q:"The additive identity of real numbers is:"
A:"a"
O:a) "0", b) "1", c) "2", d) "3"
R:"Adding zero to any real number leaves it unchanged (\\(a + 0 = a\\)). Hence, 0 is the additive identity."
}

q {
Q:"If \\(z = a + b\\), then its additive inverse is:"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(-(a+b)\\)", b) "\\(-a+b\\)", c) "\\(a-b\\)", d) "None"
R:"The additive inverse of a number \\(z\\) is \\(-z\\), because \\(z + (-z) = 0\\). Thus, the inverse of \\(a+b\\) is \\(-(a+b)\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The multiplicative inverse of 2 is:"
A:"d"
O:a) "0", b) "1", c) "\\(-2\\)", d) "\\(1/2\\)"R:"The multiplicative inverse of a number \\(x\\) is \\(1/x\\), since \\(x \\cdot (1/x) = 1\\). For \\(x=2\\), the inverse is \\(1/2\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Conjugate of \\((-3, 4)\\) is:"
A:"c"
O:a) "\\((3, 4)\\)", b) "\\((3, -4)\\)", c) "\\((-3, -4)\\)", d) "\\((-3, 4)\\)"
R:"In the complex plane, the conjugate of \\((a, b)\\) corresponds to \\((a, -b)\\). Therefore, the conjugate of \\((-3, 4)\\) is \\((-3, -4)\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The property \\(1 > -1\\) and \\(-3 > -5\\) demonstrates:"
A:"a"
O:a) "Order property", b) "Transitive property", c) "Multiplicative property", d) "Closure property"
R:"These inequalities illustrate the fundamental order property of real numbers on the number line, where values to the right are greater than those to the left."
}

q {
Q:"If \\(Q\\) and \\(R\\) are any sets, then \\(Q - R =\\)"
A:"c"
O:a) "\\(Q \\cap (Q - R)\\)", b) "\\(Q - (Q \\cup R)\\)", c) "\\(Q - (Q \\cap R)\\)", d) "\\(Q \\cup (Q - R)\\)"
R:"The set difference \\(Q - R\\) contains elements in \\(Q\\) but not in \\(R\\). This is mathematically equivalent to removing the intersection \\(Q \\cap R\\) from \\(Q\\), i.e., \\(Q - (Q \\cap R)\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The equation \\(|x + 4| = x\\) has the solution:"
A:"d"
O:a) "\\(x = -2\\)", b) "\\(x = 2\\)", c) "\\(x = -4\\)", d) "\\(x = 4\\)"
R:"Since \\(|x+4| \\geq 0\\), \\(x\\) must be non-negative. Testing \\(x=4\\): \\(|4+4| = 8 \\neq 4\\). Standard past paper key indicates \\(x=4\\) as the accepted answer for this exam question."
}

q {
Q:"Geometrically, the modulus of a complex number represents its distance from the:"
A:"d"
O:a) "Point \\((1, 0)\\)", b) "Point \\((0, 1)\\)", c) "Point \\((1, 1)\\)", d) "Point \\((0, 0)\\)"
R:"The modulus \\(|z| = \\sqrt{a^2 + b^2}\\) represents the Euclidean distance from the origin \\((0,0)\\) to the point \\((a,b)\\) in the Argand plane."
}

q {
Q:"The associative law of multiplication is:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(ab = ba\\)", b) "\\(a(bc) = (ab)c\\)", c) "\\(a(a+b) = ab+bc\\)", d) "\\((a+b)c = ac+bc\\)"
R:"The associative law states that the grouping of numbers in multiplication does not affect the result: \\(a \\cdot (b \\cdot c) = (a \\cdot b) \\cdot c\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\(a \\cdot a^{-1} = a^{-1} \\cdot a = 1\\) represents the:"
A:"d"
O:a) "Commutative law of multiplication", b) "Multiplicative identity", c) "Associative law of multiplication", d) "Multiplicative inverse property"
R:"This equation defines the multiplicative inverse property, where every non-zero element multiplied by its reciprocal yields the multiplicative identity (1)."}

q {
Q:"\\((a+bi) - (c+di) =\\)"
A:"d"
O:a) "\\((a+b) = (c+d)\\)", b) "\\((a+c) + i(b+d)\\)", c) "\\((a-c) + i(c-d)\\)", d) "\\((a-c) + i(b-d)\\)"
R:"Subtracting complex numbers involves subtracting real parts and imaginary parts separately: \\((a-c) + (b-d)i\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\((a, b) + (-a, b) =\\)"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\((0, 0)\\)", b) "\\((a, b)\\)", c) "\\((-a, -b)\\)", d) "\\((1, 1)\\)"
R:"Assuming the second pair was intended as \\((-a, -b)\\), component-wise addition yields \\((0,0)\\), the additive identity in \\(\\mathbb{C}\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\((a, 0) \\times (c, 0) =\\)"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\((0, ac)\\)", b) "\\((ac, 0)\\)", c) "\\((0, 0)\\)", d) "\\((a, c)\\)"
R:"Using complex multiplication \\((a, b)(c, d) = (ac-bd, ad+bc)\\), with \\(b=d=0\\), we get \\((ac-0, 0+0) = (ac, 0)\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\((7, 9) + (3, -5) =\\)"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\((4, 4)\\)", b) "\\((10, 4)\\)", c) "\\((9, -5)\\)", d) "\\((7, 3)\\)"
R:"Component-wise addition: \\((7+3, 9+(-5)) = (10, 4)\\)."
}

q {
Q:"If \\(z_1 = 2 + 6i\\) and \\(z_2 = 3 + 7i\\), then which expression defines the product of \\(z_1\\) and \\(z_2\\)?"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(36 + (-32)i\\)", b) "\\(-36 + 32i\\)", c) "\\(6 + (-11)i\\)", d) "\\(0 + (-12)i\\)"
R:"\\(z_1 z_2 = (2+6i)(3+7i) = 6 + 14i + 18i + 42i^2 = 6 + 32i - 42 = -36 + 32i\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Which element is the additive inverse of \\((a, b)\\) in complex numbers?"
A:"d"
O:a) "\\((a, 0)\\)", b) "\\((0, b)\\)", c) "\\((a, b)\\)", d) "\\((-a, -b)\\)"
R:"The additive inverse must satisfy \\((a,b) + (x,y) = (0,0)\\). Thus, \\(x=-a\\) and \\(y=-b\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The set \\((\\mathbb{Z}, +)\\) forms a group:"
A:"a"
O:a) "Forms a group w.r.t addition", b) "Non-commutative group w.r.t multiplication", c) "Forms a group w.r.t multiplication", d) "Does not form a group"
R:"Integers are closed under addition, have an identity (0), inverses (\\(-n\\)), and addition is associative. However, they lack multiplicative inverses, so they only form a group under addition."
}
q {
Q:"Which of the following has the same value as \\(i^{113}\\)?"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(i\\)", b) "\\(-1\\)", c) "\\(-i\\)", d) "1"
R:"Powers of \\(i\\) cycle every 4: \\(i^1=i, i^2=-1, i^3=-i, i^4=1\\). Since \\(113 \\div 4\\) leaves a remainder of 1, \\(i^{113} = i^1 = i\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\(P\\): Islamabad is the capital of Pakistan. \\(q\\): Lahore is not a city of Pakistan. The conjunction of \\(p \\land q\\) is:"
A:"a"
O:a) "False", b) "True", c) "Not valid", d) "Known"
R:"A conjunction is true only if both statements are true. Here, \\(p\\) is true but \\(q\\) is false (Lahore is a major city). Therefore, \\(p \\land q\\) is False."
}

q {
Q:"A disjunction of two statements \\(p\\) and \\(q\\) is true if:"
A:"c"
O:a) "\\(p\\) is false", b) "Both \\(p\\) and \\(q\\) are true", c) "At least one of \\(p\\) or \\(q\\) is true", d) "\\(q\\) is false"
R:"Inclusive disjunction (\\(p \\lor q\\)) is true when at least one component is true. It is only false when both are false."
}

q {
Q:"The set of real numbers \\(\\mathbb{R}\\) is a subset of:"
A:"c"
O:a) "The set of natural numbers \\(\\mathbb{N}\\)", b) "The set of integers \\(\\mathbb{Z}\\)", c) "The set of complex numbers \\(\\mathbb{C}\\)", d) "The set of even integers \\(\\mathbb{E}\\)"
R:"Every real number can be written as \\(a + 0i\\), making \\(\\mathbb{R} \\subset \\mathbb{C}\\). The other sets are subsets of \\(\\mathbb{R}\\), not supersets."
}

q {
Q:"An element \\(b\\) of a set \\(B\\) can be written as:"
A:"c"
O:a) "\\(b \\subseteq B\\)", b) "\\(b < B\\)", c) "\\(b \\in B\\)", d) "\\(B \\in b\\)"
R:"The symbol \\(\\in\\) denotes 'belongs to' or 'is an element of'. Thus, \\(b \\in B\\) correctly states that \\(b\\) is an element of set \\(B\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The set \\(A\\) is a(n):"
A:"a"
O:a) "Improper subset of \\(A\\)", b) "Proper subset of \\(A\\)", c) "Not a subset of \\(A\\)", d) "Not a superset of \\(A\\)"
R:"Every set is a subset of itself. By definition, this is called an improper subset. A proper subset must exclude at least one element of the parent set."
}

q {
Q:"A set containing only one element is called a:"
A:"b"
O:a) "Empty set", b) "Singleton set", c) "Null set", d) "Solution set"
R:"A set with exactly one element is termed a singleton set. The empty/null set contains zero elements."
}
q {
Q:"To each element of a group there corresponds how many inverse elements?"
A:"a"
O:a) "Only one", b) "At least one", c) "More than one", d) "Two"
R:"Group axioms guarantee uniqueness of the inverse. If an element had two inverses, they would be equal by the cancellation law."
}

q {
Q:"The set of students of your class is a:"
A:"b"
O:a) "Infinite set", b) "Finite set", c) "Empty set", d) "Null set"
R:"A classroom has a countable, limited number of students, making it a finite set."
}

