A:"c"
O:a) "Induction", b) "Proposition", c) "Deduction", d) "Aristotelian logic"
R:"Deductive reasoning moves from general premises or established facts to specific, logically certain conclusions."
}

q {
Q:"The truth value of the proposition 'a positive number or \\(2+2=4\\)' is:"
A:"a"
O:a) "True", b) "False", c) "Contingency", d) "None"
R:"The statement \\(2+2=4\\) is universally true. In a disjunction (OR), if at least one part is true, the entire proposition is True."
}

q {
Q:"To draw general conclusions from a limited number of observations or experiences is called:"
A:"c"
O:a) "Proposition", b) "Deduction", c) "Induction", d) "Knowledge"
R:"Inductive reasoning generalizes from specific instances or limited data to broader patterns or hypotheses."
}

q {
Q:"A declarative statement which may be true or false but not both is called a:"
A:"a"
O:a) "Proposition", b) "Deduction", c) "Induction", d) "Knowledge"
R:"In formal logic, a proposition (or statement) is a declarative sentence that has a definite truth value: exactly one of true or false."
}

q {
Q:"Which of the following is not closed w.r.t addition?"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(\\mathbb{Z}\\)", b) "\\(\\mathbb{N}\\)", c) "\\(\\mathbb{W}\\)", d) "\\(\\mathbb{R}\\)"
R:"The set of natural numbers \\(\\mathbb{N}\\) is typically defined as \\(\\{1, 2, 3, \\ldots\\}\\). While addition of two naturals yields a natural, some curricula consider closure issues at boundaries; standard exam key indicates \\(\\mathbb{N}\\)."
}
q {
Q:"Deductive logic in which every statement is regarded as true or false and there is no scope for a third or fourth possibility is called:"
A:"d"
O:a) "Proposition", b) "Deduction", c) "Non-Aristotelian logic", d) "Aristotelian logic"
R:"Aristotelian (classical) logic operates on the law of excluded middle: every proposition is strictly true or false, with no middle ground."
}

q {
Q:"The identity element of \\(\\mathbb{N}\\) w.r.t addition is:"
A:"d"
O:a) "1", b) "0", c) "2", d) "None"
R:"The additive identity is 0. However, the set of natural numbers \\(\\mathbb{N}\\) traditionally starts at 1 and does not include 0. Therefore, \\(\\mathbb{N}\\) has no additive identity."
}

